Back to school with @officialcricut #ad At my school, we are required to have learning targets posted during our lessons. Well, since I’ll be traveling, I don’t want to have to re-write “learning target” on six different whiteboards! So I made a magnet I can *literally* throw on the board and have ready to go no matter which room I’m in! Using my Cricut Maker and the new “offset” feature in Design Space, this magnet came together in no time at all! I’m ready to put it to use! #cricutmade
.

They see me rollin....... with my new cart. Losing my classroom was a huge let down, but I've loaded up my cart with everything I need for classes and there's no stopping me now! #ad I have pens, pencils, and paper on the top. Scissors, staples, and tape in the middle. Crayons, markers, and colored pencils on the bottom. And of course @classtagme so I can stay connected even if I'm on the go. With no access to a classroom phone (or even... you know... my own classroom), using @classtagme from my laptop and cell phone will be the best way to keep in touch with families. Have you ever taught from a cart before? What else should I add?
.
.
.

Want to see a picture of my classroom? Here you go. Due to sharing a room and scheduling, I will be mobile! It’s not ideal, and I’m really heartbroken over having set up an entire classroom and then not getting to use it. But I’m making the most of it. My ELA visuals will go to the ELA classroom. My math visuals will go to the math interventionist’s room (where I’ll be parking my cart one class period a day). It wasn’t the most fun news to find out the night before school started, but I’ve had a chance to let it sink in, and I think a cart of supplies is going to be my best option. If I’ve learned anything, it’s that being flexible is key. So tomorrow, I’ll load this bad boy up and get to work! Wish me luck (and send me all the coffee)
.
.
.

Three steps to becoming your students’ families’ favorite teacher! 1- Learn from them! Family input surveys are a great way to get more information about your student, and it shows you value their input. 2- Communication is key! As you begin the new school year, make sure you build those relationships from the start!

Let me show you three different ways I differentiate the same assignment. This erasable highlighter from Frixion is one of my favorite tools in my classroom. I can mark on the papers and then erase and do it again if I need to. And graphic organizers aren’t just for writing. I love this one for math to help the students with area model. Each student gets the same paper, but each paper is changed just a little bit to meet each of their needs.
.
.

node.text:
First #feetupfriday of the new school year. I started my new digital sped binder for my new caseload. I read the IEPs I currently have access to. I was trained on two new instructional programs. I hung decorations. And now, it’s time to mentally prepare. One more work day Monday and then kids come back and it’s time to dive into learning! It was the shortest summer ever (literally- only 8 weeks), but I’m excited to meet my new favorite students and see some old favorites, too. How much do you have left of your summer?
.
.
.

node.text:
Four years ago, I left my comfort zone. I left everything I had ever done in order to step into a new role. I gave up my previous tenured position to pursue my dream of being a special education teacher. And today, I earned that tenure back while living out my passion for sped in the role of a lifetime. The last three years have brought wisdom and humility and praise and tears. They have brought me some of the most incredible opportunities, amazing friends, and the best students. And to think I almost let all of this pass me by in favor of being “comfortable.” So please, take this as your sign that it’s never too late to go after your dreams, and then when you reach them, DREAM BIGGER!
.
.
.

Co-teaching model- one teach/one assist. This gets the co-teacher a little more active in the classroom, but it is still obvious that one teacher is leading the lesson. Definitely has its uses! This is the model I mostly used when working as a paraprofessional while I was finishing my degrees. It gave me a great opportunity to work with the students and learn from the lead teacher.
.
.
.
